flowRoot.flowPara: Menu Design Patterns
The aim of this page is to develop a consistent set of rules for presenting menus. In practical terms this generally means containing the menu inside a popover.
Menus have consistent styling - the same background color, spacing, corner radius.

This isn't a menu, although it is very similar to one. The only difference is that a menu would use radio buttons. There is precedence for using check marks elsewhere in GNOME, so either approach is viable.
Menus (and popovers) have a pointy bit if:
1. They refer to a small square or round shape.
2. They are positioned in relation to a control rather than the location that was clicked.
General rules
Not menus

These examples are not menus. However, they are similar in various respects and follow some of the same principles. It is therefore useful to document them here, both in order to ensure consistency and to define what a menu is and isn't.

A menu is a list of clickable, simple, text items. These can have check boxes or radio buttons attached to them. Over the years this definition has evolved a little, so that they sometimes they can have buttons at the top or inline. However, their essence remains the same.
